{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"coaching":[{"coaching":"Plan how verification gaps in acceptance criteria will be verified in-session — restate any deferred or unobservable success target as an observable proxy.","decision":"advisory","finding_refs":["f607dd457c67f9209"],"move_id":"9","move_name":"plan the verification","subject":"verification gaps in acceptance criteria"}],"coverage":{"counts":{"advisory_overflow":0,"advisory_surfaced":1,"blocking":0,"dropped":0,"indeterminate":15},"det":{"P1":{"ac_items":6,"blocking":false,"clarity_score":7,"name":"readiness-shape","ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P2":{"blocking":false,"name":"resolution","ran":true,"references":0,"resolved":0,"status":"pass"},"P3":{"blocking":false,"name":"package-existence","packages":0,"ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P4":{"ac_items":6,"blocking":false,"desc_chars":5812,"file_impact":14,"name":"oversize","ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P5":{"blocking":false,"children":0,"name":"task-dag","ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P6":{"ac_items":6,"blocking":false,"name":"ac-quality","ran":true,"status":"fail","verify_commands_linted":4,"verify_lint_abstained":4},"P7":{"blocking":false,"destructive_hits":[],"name":"destructive-sniff","ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P8":{"blocking":false,"budget_tokens":868000,"name":"reviewability","plan_tokens":1467,"ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P9":{"applicable":true,"blocking":false,"file_impact":14,"name":"file-impact-coverage","ran":true,"status":"pass"}},"llm_ran":true,"metrics":{"claim_path":"no-llm/no-network (structural; the fast claim check is a local HMAC verify)","det_ms":258.6,"llm_calls":30,"llm_ms":524147.2,"total_ms":524529.5,"verify_requests":31},"remediation":{"baseline":"sidecar","eligible":false,"reasons":{"code_unchanged":false,"plan_changed":false,"registry_unchanged":false,"sidecar_baseline":false,"within_window":false}},"routing":{"agent_tier":["A1","E4","G1G2","G6","G7","T1","T10","T11","T13","T14","T3","T5c","T8","removal-rationale"],"single_turn":["COH","E1","E2","E3","E5","E6","F1","F4","G5","T2","T4","T5b","T5d","T5e","T6","T7","T9","hedge"]}},"findings":[{"block_threshold":null,"blocking_enabled":null,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["P6"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["5 criterion line(s) bundle multiple deliverables with 'and' (split so each is independently verifiable)."],"finding":"Acceptance-criteria / definition-of-done quality issues.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f607dd457c67f9209","impact":0.4,"is_primary":null,"location":"","norm_id":"ned06ebc801a522e3","priority":0.4,"reason":null,"scenarios":[],"severity":"minor","suggested_fix":"Split compound criteria, replace subjective terms with observable outcomes, and state how each is verified.","tier":"DET","validity":1.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.6,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add a proving command to AC5 that verifies doc correctness, e.g. `grep -E '\\bcli\\b.*\\bmcp\\b.*\\bpython\\b' docs/event-schema.md docs/output-schemas.md` or a dedicated contract test that parses the doc and asserts all six enum values are present.","cohort":["E2","E6","F1"],"criteria":["E6","F1"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["AC5 text: 'ticket_state JSON Schema, generated TicketState types, show/list/search/export outputs, and docs expose the same six-value enum'","Proving commands listed: only pytest schema contract tests and gen_types --check","Files section lists docs/event-schema.md and docs/output-schemas.md as targets but no command validates their content"],"finding":"AC5 claims that 'docs expose the same six-value enum and true-only optional inference marker' but the proving command (`pytest ... test_schema_*.py && python -m rebar.schemas.gen_types --check`) exercises only schema/type artifacts — no command verifies that docs/event-schema.md and docs/output-schemas.md actually contain the correct enum values.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f7b52be666ec77d44","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Acceptance Criteria, AC5; Files section (docs/event-schema.md, docs/output-schemas.md)","norm_id":"nef75ec48fa81f000","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["Agent updates the schema and types correctly but leaves docs stale or incomplete; all AC5 proving commands pass, but the docs claim is silently unproven.","A reviewer checks docs/event-schema.md and finds the enum incomplete or absent — but the story was marked done."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Add to the AC5 proving command: `&& grep -cE '(cli|mcp|python|jira|import|unknown)' docs/event-schema.md docs/output-schemas.md` (or a small pytest parametrize over the six values) so doc coverage is deterministically verified in-session.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Confirm `python -m rebar.schemas.gen_types --check` is an existing supported mode (or add it to the Files list and What section), and state in the plan that the flag exits non-zero when generated output differs from on-disk types.py.","cohort":["E2","E6","F1"],"criteria":["E6"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["AC5 proving command: 'python -m rebar.schemas.gen_types --check'","Files section lists src/rebar/types.py as 'generated output only via python -m rebar.schemas.gen_types' but does not list gen_types.py as a file to be modified","Plan says 'regenerate src/rebar/types.py through the existing schema generator' — implying --check is pre-existing, but this is unconfirmed"],"finding":"AC5's proving command references `python -m rebar.schemas.gen_types --check`, but the Files list does not include `src/rebar/schemas/gen_types.py` (or equivalent) as a file to modify, and the plan does not state that a `--check` / diff mode already exists in the generator. If the flag is absent, the command will either error out or silently succeed without checking anything.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fee4066de3060ff59","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Acceptance Criteria, AC5; Files section","norm_id":"n91cd9293f6e7eb77","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["gen_types does not support --check; the command exits 0 (unknown flag ignored) or exits non-zero (breaks CI for the wrong reason); either way the AC is either silently un-proven or spuriously failing."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"If --check does not exist, add `src/rebar/schemas/gen_types.py` to the Files list with the note 'add --check flag: regenerate to a temp file, diff against types.py, exit 1 on any difference.' Alternatively replace the AC command with a shell idiom: `python -m rebar.schemas.gen_types --stdout | diff - src/rebar/types.py`.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add an explicit rollback / back-out statement to the plan (e.g., 'schema changes are purely additive; reverting the code leaves stored creation_channel keys as harmless extra data ignored by the prior reducer, and regenerating types from the reverted schema restores the prior public types').","cohort":["T2","T4","T7"],"criteria":["T4"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan states changes are 'additive' but provides no back-out sequence if a defective deploy must be reversed after some events have been written with the new field.","AC5 requires `python -m rebar.schemas.gen_types --check`, confirming types are regenerated — but no rollback of that regeneration is described.","Approach Rationale says 'unknown is reserved for historical compatibility' — this implies rollback safety, but the plan never makes the argument explicit or states the rollback procedure."],"finding":"The plan has no explicit rollback or back-out path for the schema changes and type regeneration step, even though they are described as additive. For an auditable foundation story that modifies stored event structure and regenerates public types, the plan should state how to safely revert if the deploy is defective.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f3c70c16b21168c23","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Approach Rationale / Files (src/rebar/schemas/common.schema.json, ticket_state.schema.json, src/rebar/types.py)","norm_id":"nf367175bbe0b3767","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["A defective deploy writes events with creation_channel in CREATE.data; rolling back the code leaves the prior reducer encountering unexpected keys — the plan should confirm this is safe (extra JSON keys are ignored) and state so explicitly.","If ticket_state.schema.json is reverted post-deploy, any client that cached the new schema will see validation failures on the new optional fields."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Add a 'Rollback' subsection under Approach Rationale: 'Because all schema changes are purely additive (new optional fields, new enum type), reverting to the prior code version is safe — the prior reducer ignores unknown keys in CREATE.data, and `python -m rebar.schemas.gen_types` from the reverted schema restores prior generated types. No data migration or compensating event is needed.'","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add an ADR (or CLAUDE.md section) capturing the explicit-channel-threading decision — including the rejected alternatives (stack inspection, context-local state) and the rule that every new ingress boundary must supply its channel at the call site — so that dependent Jira/import/compaction stories have a normative reference.","cohort":["T5b","T5e","T9"],"criteria":["T5e"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["\"Explicit boundary threading is chosen because the interface knows the channel and the shared core does not.\"","\"This is the foundation for the Jira/import and compaction stories.\"","Files list includes docs/event-schema.md and docs/output-schemas.md but no ADR, CLAUDE.md, or internal design-doc update.","The decision to use keyword-only explicit threading (vs context-local state, middleware, or stack inspection) is a cross-cutting architectural choice that will govern how every future ingress story attributes its channel."],"finding":"The plan introduces a new foundational architectural pattern — explicit channel threading as the canonical attribution mechanism for all creation paths — and designates itself the dependency base for Jira, import, and compaction stories, yet no ADR or CLAUDE.md update is planned; only end-user schema docs are listed.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fa1e315b401613199","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Files section: docs/event-schema.md and docs/output-schemas.md; Approach Rationale section; Dependencies section","norm_id":"nd5b66b23e87336df","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["A future story author implementing the Jira or import channel has no authoritative internal doc explaining why stack inspection was rejected and how to correctly thread the channel parameter — likely to re-litigate or deviate from the pattern.","A reviewer of the compaction story has no ADR to cite when evaluating whether a new ingress path follows the established convention."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Create docs/adr/NNNN-creation-channel-threading.md (or a `## Creation Channel Attribution` section in CLAUDE.md) that records: (1) the decision to thread channel as a keyword-only parameter, (2) the rejected alternatives and why, (3) the rule that `unknown` is illegal for new live writes, and (4) a pointer to the closed enum in common.schema.json. Reference it from the Files list in this plan.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Confirm whether `jira` and `import` enum members should be added now (as a forward-contract for dependent stories) or deferred until those stories land writers; if deferred, reduce the enum to `cli, mcp, python, unknown` for this story.","cohort":["A1"],"criteria":["A1"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan Scope OUT: 'Jira inbound creation, NDJSON import ... Those are assigned to later children or explicitly excluded by the epic.'","Plan What: enum includes 'jira, import' in this story's deliverable","AC4: 'New local writers reject unknown or values outside the closed enum' — but jira/import have no writers in this story, so the enum contains forward-declared-but-unused members","YAGNI: enum members serve a future done-definition (Jira/import children), not this story's done-definition"],"finding":"The canonical enum includes `jira` and `import` members, but no writers for those channels ship in this story (Jira inbound creation and NDJSON import are explicitly OUT-scoped). Adding these enum members now means the closed-enum validator must accept values that have no producing call site yet, making the 'reject unknown or values outside the closed enum' AC moot for half the vocabulary in this story.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fb21c851d124cd83c","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"What section: 'Add the canonical creation-channel enum to src/rebar/schemas/common.schema.json with exactly cli, mcp, python, jira, import, unknown'","norm_id":"nadfb1f1d361d5a8f","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["A Jira story author later adds `jira` writers and finds the enum already present — no problem. But if the Jira story's design changes the value name or semantics, the schema contract is already published and harder to revise.","The closed-enum validator tests in this story only exercise cli/mcp/python/unknown; jira/import members go untested until the child stories land, making the 'closed' claim partially aspirational."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Consider deferring `creation_channel_inferred` from the ticket_state schema and generated types until the Jira inference story that actually produces it; this story only needs `creation_channel` (the primary field).","cohort":["A1"],"criteria":["A1"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan What: 'A legacy CREATE with no value projects creation_channel=unknown and does not carry creation_channel_inferred.'","Plan What: 'recorded and unknown projections omit it' — meaning this story produces zero instances of creation_channel_inferred=true in output","Plan Scope OUT: 'historical Jira inference' is out of scope","YAGNI: the field serves a future done-definition (Jira inference child story), not this story's AC"],"finding":"`creation_channel_inferred` (the `{\\\"const\\\": true}` inference marker field) is specified in ticket_state schema for this story, but has zero writers — the plan explicitly states 'recorded and unknown projections omit it' and the inference logic belongs to the Jira/import story (OUT-scoped). Specifying the output-schema field before any writer exists is premature schema surface.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f419aae197222081f","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"What section: 'Encode the marker as {\"const\": true}; recorded and unknown projections omit it.' / Files: src/rebar/schemas/ticket_state.schema.json","norm_id":"n580e281de32c2bbf","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["The Jira inference story lands and finds the field name or encoding already locked in the public schema, but with a different preferred design (e.g. the const:true encoding is revisited). The public schema must then be revised with a migration.","Contract tests in AC5 must document/validate a field that is never populated by any writer in this story, which adds test surface for a zero-writer field."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add `src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/apply_inbound_records.py` to the Files section and explicitly document that its `rebar.ensure_identity_for(...)` call will receive `creation_channel='python'` by default — acknowledge this as intentional (deferred to the Jira story) or supply a forward-compatible placeholder (e.g. `creation_channel='unknown'`) for the Jira-inbound path.","cohort":["G1G2"],"criteria":["G1G2"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan Files section lists identity.py but NOT apply_inbound_records.py","apply_inbound_records.py line 69: rebar.ensure_identity_for('jira', account_id, display_name or account_id, repo_root=repo_root) — no creation_channel argument","Plan Scope OUT explicitly defers Jira inbound creation to a later story, but this file will be silently affected as soon as ensure_identity_for gains a default creation_channel='python'"],"finding":"src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/apply_inbound_records.py calls rebar.ensure_identity_for() for Jira-inbound ghost minting and is not listed in the Files section. When this story adds creation_channel='python' as the default to ensure_identity_for's signature, that call site will silently record creation_channel='python' for identities minted by the Jira inbound reconciler — the wrong channel for audit purposes.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f8d5fcc571bb7fbdd","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Files section / src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/apply_inbound_records.py:69","norm_id":"n59d35b0b48338739","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["After this story ships, every Jira-inbound ghost identity minted by the reconciler will carry creation_channel='python' in its CREATE.data, poisoning the audit record before the Jira story can supply 'jira'.","The Jira attribution story will need to retroactively correct already-written events, or accept stale 'python' labels on pre-existing ghost identities."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Verify (or extend) `gen_types.py` handles `{\"const\": true}` optional properties, and document the expected TypedDict emission (e.g., `NotRequired[Literal[True]]`) for `creation_channel_inferred` in the plan or in the generator.","cohort":["T1"],"criteria":["T1"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan text: 'Encode the marker as {\"const\": true}; recorded and unknown projections omit it. Regenerate derived public types'","gen_types.py docstring (lines 9-31): 'Custom, dependency-free. We resolve exactly the constructs rebar's schemas use (cross-file $ref into common.schema.json#/$defs/*, [\"T\",\"null\"] unions, enum $ref → Literal[...], arrays)' — `const` is not listed.","ABSENCE: no `const` handling is visible in the generator's described constructs, and the plan makes no note of extending the generator."],"finding":"The plan specifies encoding `creation_channel_inferred` as `{\"const\": true}` in `ticket_state.schema.json` and states the existing `gen_types.py` will regenerate correct derived types, but `gen_types.py`'s custom translator is documented to handle only specific JSON Schema constructs (cross-file `$ref`, `[\"T\",\"null\"]` unions, enum `$ref` → `Literal`, arrays). Whether it correctly translates a `{\"const\": true}` optional property to a TypedDict field (e.g., `NotRequired[Literal[True]]`) is not verified in the plan or generator documentation — making this an unverified capability assertion.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fcf5ce71e7474e843","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"What section / 'Add optional public schema fields ... Encode the marker as {\"const\": true} ... Regenerate derived public types'","norm_id":"n005c7dc57d1e12b8","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["Running `python -m rebar.schemas.gen_types` after adding the `{\"const\": true}` field either silently drops `creation_channel_inferred` from the TypedDict or emits it with the wrong type annotation (e.g., `Any` or `bool`), causing the AC5 `--check` step to either pass with a wrong type or fail unexpectedly.","A downstream consumer relying on the generated TypedDict for type-checking gets an incorrect or absent annotation for the inference marker."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Add a note to the plan: 'Extend `gen_types.py` to map `{\"const\": true}` → `Literal[True]` (or `Literal[false]` etc.) so the inference marker is correctly typed; verify with the `--check` AC5 step.' Alternatively, encode the inference marker as `{\"type\": \"boolean\"}` with a description constraint, which the generator already handles via `bool`.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Specify how persisted compiled-state snapshots are invalidated or version-tagged when `creation_channel` is introduced, and assert the expected snapshot schema state after a rollback (not merely that rollback exits 0).","cohort":["T11"],"criteria":["T11"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["'OUT: ... SNAPSHOT durability ...' — explicitly deferred, no invalidation or versioning strategy given","'project it into compiled state' — implies compiled state is written somewhere, but rollback behaviour of that written state is unaddressed","No mention of snapshot cache-busting, version tagging, or forced recomputation on schema change"],"finding":"The plan explicitly places 'SNAPSHOT durability' out of scope but does not specify how persisted compiled-state snapshots are invalidated or versioned when `creation_channel` is added. If snapshots are stored and used as a read cache, old snapshots will be missing the field; on rollback, new snapshots containing `creation_channel` would be read by old code that does not understand the field. The plan makes no assertion about the post-rollback snapshot schema state, leaving a potential DATA LOSS RISK if snapshots are the authoritative read path.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fa11288edc6852ed7","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Scope section ('OUT: ... SNAPSHOT durability') and Files section (reducer/_processors.py)","norm_id":"nf6a3a441dfa6a8d1","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["Code is deployed, some tickets gain `creation_channel` in their compiled snapshots, then code is rolled back; old code reads a snapshot it cannot interpret and either silently drops the field or errors","Rollback exits 0 but leaves snapshots in an incorrect intermediate state (mixed old/new shape)"],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Assert that the pre-rollback (old) CREATE event schema tolerates the new `creation_channel` field (e.g., via `additionalProperties` policy), or document the rollback procedure explicitly as 'forward-only / compensate-forward' with a DATA LOSS RISK note for events written during the upgrade window.","cohort":["T11"],"criteria":["T11"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan adds `creation_channel` to common.schema.json as a closed enum — old schema does not have this field","'Existing creation behavior, error semantics, and event canonicalization remain unchanged' (AC-6) only proves forward behavior, not rollback forward-compatibility","No forward-compatibility or 'unknown field tolerance' assertion in the event schema or reducer is mentioned"],"finding":"The plan does not assert forward-compatibility of the CREATE event format for rolled-back code. After deployment, new CREATE events will carry `creation_channel` in their data. If the code is rolled back, the old reducer/validator reads these new events against the old schema (which lacks the field). If the old schema uses `additionalProperties: false` or equivalent strict validation, new events will fail to parse, breaking reads of any ticket created after the upgrade.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"ff2025171237cb19c","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Files: src/rebar/schemas/common.schema.json, reducer/_processors.py; Acceptance Criteria AC-6 (canonicalization test)","norm_id":"n1be4883fa7fc7a8c","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["Rollback after partial deployment; tickets created in the deployment window have `creation_channel` in CREATE.data; old code strict-validates and rejects those events on read","show/list/search/export commands silently skip or hard-error on post-upgrade tickets after a rollback"],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add a `const` keyword handler to `gen_types.py`'s `_pytype()` method (e.g. `if 'const' in node: return repr(node['const'])` with `Literal` import) so `{\"const\": true}` produces `Literal[True]` in the generated TicketState, and list `src/rebar/schemas/gen_types.py` as a file to modify.","cohort":["T3"],"criteria":["T3"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan: 'Encode the marker as {\"const\": true}; recorded and unknown projections omit it. Regenerate derived public types'","gen_types.py _pytype() method (lines 115–149): handles '$ref', 'enum', 'type' (list/array/object/None) — no branch for 'const'","A {\"const\": true} node has neither 'type' nor 'enum', so _pytype() reaches `jtype is None` → returns 'Any', emitting NotRequired[Any] in TicketState instead of NotRequired[Literal[True]]","Evidence class: Verified (observed in gen_types.py source)"],"finding":"The `gen_types.py` generator has no `const` keyword handler: a `{\"const\": true}` schema node (the proposed encoding for `creation_channel_inferred`) falls through to the `jtype is None` branch and is emitted as `Any`, not `Literal[True]`. AC5 asserts the generated TicketState type exposes a 'true-only optional inference marker', but the generator as written cannot produce that.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f0684b48426430763","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"What / Files sections: ticket_state.schema.json + src/rebar/types.py via python -m rebar.schemas.gen_types; AC5: 'generated TicketState types … expose the same six-value enum and true-only optional inference marker'","norm_id":"n0c12218e91978e0f","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["AC5 pytest run (`test_schema_ticket_state.py`, `test_schema_outputs.py`, `--check` mode) fails because the generated file contains `NotRequired[Any]` for `creation_channel_inferred` instead of `NotRequired[Literal[True]]`.","Type-checker consumers of TicketState get `Any` for the inference marker field, defeating the typed-contract goal."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"In `_pytype()`, add before the `jtype = node.get('type')` line: `if 'const' in node: self._used_typing.add('Literal'); return f\"Literal[{node['const']!r}]\"`. This matches the existing `enum` handling pattern and produces `Literal[True]` for `{\"const\": true}`.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Co-locate the 'unknown is rejected for new live writes' rule in the composer.py file spec (or the _version.py runtime-constant spec): explicitly state that create_core's channel validation rejects 'unknown' (and any out-of-enum value), separate from the JSON Schema enum which permits 'unknown' for read/output.","cohort":["T8"],"criteria":["T8"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["'unknown is reserved for historical compatibility and is rejected for new live writes' appears only in Approach Rationale, not in the What-section schema spec or the create_core file spec","common.schema.json currently has no creation_channel $def and no validator note","composer.create_core currently has no channel validation — the plan spec for that file says 'validate and write explicit channel; CLI create passes cli' but does not say where the enum check is anchored"],"finding":"The write-rejection decision rule ('unknown is rejected for new live writes') is co-located only in Approach Rationale prose, not adjacent to the schema definition (common.schema.json $def) or the validator call-site in composer.create_core. An implementer must hunt across two plan sections to assemble the full validation contract.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f8361617b26b6bc1f","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Plan 'What' section / 'Approach Rationale' section; src/rebar/_commands/composer.py create_core; src/rebar/schemas/common.schema.json","norm_id":"nc1adb80094cda8c8","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["An implementer adds the enum to common.schema.json but does not wire the 'unknown rejected at write time' rule into create_core because the schema itself (using JSON Schema enum) would allow 'unknown' as a valid value — the runtime rejection is a SEPARATE constraint not expressed in the schema.","A future caller passes channel='unknown' to create_core and receives no error because the schema validator passes it and the prose rule was overlooked."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"In the 'Files' section for composer.py, add: 'Validate that creation_channel is in the closed enum AND is not \"unknown\" (which is read-only/legacy-projection-only); raise CommandError with error_code=\"invalid_creation_channel\" on either violation.'","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Specify which enum values are accepted at new local-write boundaries: either state explicitly that only {cli, mcp, python} are accepted by create_core for new local writes (jira/import/unknown all rejected), or define a separate 'local-write-allowed' subset in the _version.py constants spec alongside the full enum.","cohort":["T8"],"criteria":["T8"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Enum: 'exactly cli, mcp, python, jira, import, unknown'","Scope OUT: 'Jira inbound creation, NDJSON import' are excluded from this story","No file in the 'Files' list corresponds to a jira or import writer","Approach Rationale: 'unknown is reserved for historical compatibility and is rejected for new live writes' — this implicitly applies to jira/import too but is never stated"],"finding":"The enum includes 'jira' and 'import' but no local writer is specified for these values within this story's scope, and the rejection rule ('rejected for new live writes') means they can NEVER be emitted by any writer defined here. There is no decision rule specifying how create_core's validator should handle these values — reject them the same as 'unknown', or accept them for future Jira/import call sites?","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fad75422de5eccd63","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Plan 'What' section (enum definition) / 'Scope OUT' section; src/rebar/schemas/common.schema.json; src/rebar/_commands/composer.py","norm_id":"n2cd6f09b4a0c70b4","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["Implementer adds 'jira' and 'import' to the enum but creates_core's validator only rejects 'unknown', allowing a buggy local caller to pass channel='jira' and persist it — an audit channel that no local interface should ever emit.","Implementer rejects all values not in {cli, mcp, python} for new local writes, which is correct, but this is not specified — a future Jira story may then need to change the rejection rule rather than just adding a writer."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Add to the _version.py spec in 'Files': 'Add CREATION_CHANNEL_LOCAL_WRITERS = frozenset({\"cli\", \"mcp\", \"python\"}) as the write-gate set; create_core validates against this subset, not the full enum. jira and import are reserved for future non-local writers and are refused by the local gate.'","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Specify whether rebar.create_identity in _lib_writes.py gains a channel parameter (for MCP override), or whether _mcp_writes.py bypasses the public facade and calls create_identity_core directly — both are viable but the plan must choose one so the MCP identity creation path reliably records 'mcp'.","cohort":["T8"],"criteria":["T8"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Current _mcp_writes.py create_identity calls rebar.create_identity(name, email, ..., return_alias=True) — no channel param","Current _lib_writes.py create_identity calls _identity.create_identity_core(...) — no channel param","Plan says 'Python defaults to python; CLI handlers pass cli; MCP create_ticket, create_idea, and log_session pass mcp' — but create_identity's MCP-to-library channel threading is not described","'Add creation_channel=\"python\" keyword parameters to create_identity_core and ensure_identity_for' — stated, but the intermediate rebar.create_identity facade is not addressed"],"finding":"The channel threading path from MCP's create_identity tool through rebar.create_identity (_lib_writes.py) to _identity.create_identity_core is unspecified. The plan says '_mcp_writes.py: MCP boundary attribution' and 'create_identity_core/ensure_identity_for channel signatures, Python defaults', but rebar.create_identity in _lib_writes.py calls _identity.create_identity_core directly without any channel parameter today — the intermediate public function's new signature and how MCP overrides its default are not specified.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f7095ebb3df6dcd2b","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Plan 'Files' section: src/rebar/_lib_writes.py and src/rebar/_commands/identity.py; src/rebar/_mcp_writes.py lines 83-85","norm_id":"n660ef6182aff6af6","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["Implementer adds channel kwarg to create_identity_core but forgets to add it to rebar.create_identity in _lib_writes.py, so MCP's create_identity cannot pass 'mcp' through the facade.","The rebar.create_identity public API gets a channel param that is not listed in the public API docs, breaking the public contract."],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add a co-located three-row decision table in the reducer/_processors.py file spec (or the schema spec) that maps each projection case to its exact output: (1) CREATE.data has valid channel → emit channel, omit inferred; (2) CREATE.data has no channel (None/missing) → emit channel='unknown', omit inferred; (3) CREATE.data has unrecognized string → define behavior (e.g., treat as case 2).","cohort":["T8"],"criteria":["T8"],"decision":"indeterminate","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["'A legacy CREATE with no value projects creation_channel=unknown and does not carry creation_channel_inferred'","'Encode the marker as {\"const\": true}; recorded and unknown projections omit it'","The term 'recorded' is used but never defined — it appears to mean a CREATE that carried an explicit channel, but this is not stated","There is no explicit rule for the case where CREATE.data.creation_channel is an unrecognized string (not in enum)"],"finding":"The projection rule for creation_channel_inferred is stated across two separate sections ('Store creation_channel in CREATE.data…' and 'Add optional public schema fields') with no single authoritative decision table. Specifically: the three projection cases (channel present → emit it, legacy no-channel → emit unknown + no inferred, recorded → emit recorded) are split between prose paragraphs and the schema note, leaving the exact condition for omitting creation_channel_inferred ambiguous ('recorded and unknown projections omit it' — but 'recorded' is not a defined term).","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f30f13641a6cc4e5e","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Plan 'What' section: 'Store creation_channel in CREATE.data for every new local creation' and 'Add optional public schema fields creation_channel and creation_channel_inferred'","norm_id":"n358a409b9b1d3fb8","priority":0.0,"reason":"no-verification","scenarios":["Implementer is uncertain whether 'recorded' means 'any non-null value' or 'a valid enum value' — a CREATE with creation_channel='legacy_custom' would produce an unknown projection state","An implementer adds creation_channel_inferred to the unknown projection, contradicting the schema spec but consistent with a naive reading of 'inferred = we had to guess'"],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.0,"verification":null}],"impact_model_version":"plan-v3","material_fingerprint":"547476e26caf04e0","metrics":{"claim_path":"no-llm/no-network (structural; the fast claim check is a local HMAC verify)","det_ms":258.6,"llm_calls":30,"llm_ms":524147.2,"total_ms":524529.5,"verify_requests":31},"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","regver":"b293b9a55de591cc","runner":"pydantic_ai","schema":"plan_review_result_v2","ticket_id":"6fe2-ab22-c231-4a41","ticket_type":"story","verdict":"PASS","verified_at_sha":"8bb261c19e933b5705a14c0625e9919e0d53634a"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"REVIEW_RESULT","timestamp":1784264224138635001,"uuid":"f24f08e4-f8c6-4069-8ac9-78eff35a57af"}